tells us that tradition has value, but he didn't delve into the underlying epistemological mechanisms: why tradition contains wisdom, and why rational planning fails. Hayek, an Austrian economist and 1974 Nobel laureate in economics, systematically answered this question in the 20th century. His core contribution to the critique of modernity is a seemingly simple yet profoundly influential insight: the problem of knowledge. In 1945, Hayek published a paper, "The Application of Knowledge in Society," a work of less than 20 pages that fundamentally changed our understanding of planned economies. He posed the question:

73
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:40,900
Why is central planning impossible? Note that it's not about

