specific and tacit. Let me

79
00:06:37,700 --> 00:06:39,433
give you an example: a farmer in a mountain village in Yunnan who has been growing tea for 30 years. What does he know? He knows the soil characteristics of this hillside, and he knows which plots of land are suitable for which varieties. Knowing there's been more rain this year, how to adjust the harvest time, knowing which month's tea is of the best quality—this knowledge is specific, accumulated from 30 years of experience. Can you write this knowledge into a

80
00:06:39,966 --> 00:06:42,466
manual? You

81
00:06:50,166 --> 00:06:51,900
can, but you can never fully convey it because it involves too many subtle judgments, too many unspoken secrets.

82
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:58,966
This is what Michael Polanyi calls tacit knowledge—that is, we know far more than we can articulate. Now the question arises: how can an

83
00:06:59,466 --> 00:07:01,666
agricultural bureaucrat sitting in Beijing grasp the

84
